Ive been broken for many years! After several bad falls from my horses including breaking my back,  I also suffer from sciatica, adding in lots horrible fertility investigations and IVF then having a little miracle baby at 38!.  I just assumed I would be painful, stiff and old forever! 
I had got to the stage of not been able to sleep! My hips and back were so painful and thanks to an emergency Caesarian section I had no core.. Walking any distance was impossible never mind riding again. Even before this I struggled with anxiety and insomnia. I lived on medication and was basically told by the doctors that this was my life and to get used to it. 
However a friend recommended I tried Yoga with Adriene . Her word were " you will love it she even has a doggy helper" .. Well after that I just had to try. So for the last two months I have been doing the odd video a few times a week and Im hooked. I started with the beginner video and then I started the Dedicate 30 day videos. Im like a different person! I can touch my toes again! I think the last time I managed that I was a child. I no longer have to take medication to sleep and after not riding for over two years Im back on board and my core is probably better than it has ever been. Thank you Adriene (and of course Benji) you have given me my mind, body and life back. Xxx

Been doing yoga every day during lockdown here in the UK. Started with Home then had a couple of months looking at your individual videos then decided to do another 30 day challenge. Felt like these last few days I have just been going through the motions of yoga, I've been physically in the poses but not mentally felt like I've shown up. Got a little hard on myself for not being open to the practice. Hell, I've been hard on myself for not being present in my day to day life, I've been sad, stressed, scared and everything that comes with this pandemic, and still I hated myself for not being more, feeling more or doing more. 
Today the poses were everything I needed and I felt like my spirit had come back to the work. I feel so much more alive and happy after this practice!
When Adriene said HIP DIPS, I was like NOOOOO I do not want to. I hate these, I cant do it. 
Her saying 'the struggle is real, it's part of life. but its how we handle it' just made me realise and appreciate all the planks and difficult postures she gives us to practice. It really doesn't matter if you can do it or not. How do you handle those difficult positions? Do you give up, do you cheat? Do you half arse it? And that reflects a lot of what we do in real life. Id just never connected the two. 
Safe to say I then tried the hip dips and was no swan whilst doing so. But I had a smile on my face and laughed when I fell. 
THANK YOU ADRIENE AND THIS WONDERFUL COMMUNITY
Namaste

It's taken a lot of me playing with it to get anything that felt right, and finally I gave up winging it and measured myself from palm to shoulder, shoulder to hip and hip to heel. A few sketches and some trig later, I realized I needed to start trying the pose with a much longer dog. My in sketched guess was too long (I'm 1.93 m tall and figured about 1.5 m from hands to feet), but I walked it back maybe 20 cm and the pose started making a lot more sense than it had before. I'm not sure this is exactly what Adriene meant with find your own way and what feels good, but hey it certainly helped!

Man what an awesome practice. I got to about day 9 the first time through because I got really really sick. The second time through I wanted to start out from the top and now it's day 15. For the first time ever, I've made it this far without skipping one single day and boy am I proud of myself.


Today I looked at myself properly in the mirror for the first time in a while and was shocked at how much I'd changed (all in good ways!). I'm leaner but more than that, my face seems softer and more relaxed even on days that get me down like today. I have the skills to move with grace through bad days which I've been cultivating of late by showing up to do yoga even on bad days and working to find whatever inner smile I've got today. That grace allows me to get stuff done without grinding myself into the ground trying to make it happen. That makes me proud too.


Then there's the way that I feel. Sore, mostly! But I always feel better after my evening yoga session and day my day, old soreness has been going away for new ones. I remember the first week that my feet were killing me, then my shoulders. Now it's more my hips and knees. I can't say I'm excited for where I'll be sore next but I can say that I'm proud that even though we're still working our feet and our shoulders more than when we started, they hurt less. I notice the changes to how my body moves. I climb the stairs differently, my core is active when I walk, I keep my back straighter and my shoulder further down my back when I sit at work. When I bend over the sink to wash my face, my body automatically moves to a flat back instead of hunching over.


And of course today's practice brought all those little changes home. Taking us back through cornerstones of the practices thus far and letting us feel how much easier they are now and of course introducing the forearm planks with hip dips to keep us honest about the journey forwards. The core flow from tabletop was so tough the first couple of times we did it but it felt awesome today. The one for downwards dog took some effort but it was so much harder than ones I shook through in days past.


All of this in just 15 days. What a wonderful practice and way of encouraging us to reflect on ourselves. Thank you.

So, I am sad and ashamed to say that I gave up, on myself and as a result on this journey, for a few days. An event in my personally life made me feel ashamed, sad, disappointed in myself  and stupid and it made me not show up on day 15 through17. Then, I felt sad and ashamed for not showing up and got myself stuck in a thought spiral of "should I just start again from the beginning? Start from where I left off and keep up with the one video a day, even if I'm late compared to everybody? Or should I do as many videos as I can for a few days to try and catch up to everyone?". I put so much pressure on myself that it took me a few more days to get back on the mat. But here I am, 6 days later. I have chosen to remind myself of the teachings of yoga (this is a practice, I should keep practicing without thinking of things in terms of success or failure, and I should find what feels good) and of my intentions when I started this process. So I am back, and it feels good. I loved this practice. Thank you Adriene, and I'm sorry for these few days of wandering and losing myself a bit, off the path.

I can't believe we're only halfway through! This is my first time committing to consistent yoga practice though I've been doing it on and off for the past year, but my physical therapist recommended I pick it up for my chronic back pain. After two weeks I'm already feeling much better on average with my pain, and also am noticing myself becoming stronger, more flexible, and just feeling more confidant in myself and my body in general. The confidence that yoga is giving me is also making me crave other physical activity, and giving me better performance in other activities because of the patience and self awareness that I feel I'm gaining through yoga practice. Super surprised to be this in love with it! I'm going on a road trip next week for the next month and something like that would normally interrupt my routines and break new good habits, but I'm already planning out ways that I can get my daily yoga in regardless of where I am. Thank you!

Halfway in, and still keeping up! Missing a few days here and there because life gets in the way -- but I've been excited to do a double session some days.

I've really been enjoying following along. So much so, that I've been inspired to upgrade my own fitness webapp project I'm developing to incorporate logging yoga activities. I'd be very excited to get you involved in the platform that it all operates on. I'm not sure if you've heard of it or not -- but it's running on an open-source blockchain called Steem, where content creators and content consumers are both rewarded (to varying degrees) for their social engagement.

Check out https://steem.io -- and specifically, the webapp / dApp (where the 'd' stands for 'decentralized') called dTube (https://d.tube) where users post, share, and consume videos similar to YouTube. The site I've slowly been developing (mostly, at this point, related to running and cycling) at https://xhaust.me.

I'm not certain if this is the best way to get a hold of you. If there's a better way to reach out -- please let me know. I don't often comment on YouTube -- so I'm not certain if there's a private-message type feature available, or if your email is listed somewhere.

If you're not overly interested -- that's fine too! I'll keep following along and try to bolster my home practice :)

Cheers!

Just had an epiphany. I do marathon running and I learned years ago that if, at the beginning or start of the marathon, if my focus is on the finish line, I'll either never make it, or I'll finish but it will be a much harder run. When I do not focus on the result, on the ending, and live in the moment, that's when I made my record-setting runs for myself. One year I finished at 4hr30 min, and the next 3hr20min. I was wondering why I was able to commit to Yoga With Adriene moreso this year than others and I realized that Adriene has been teaching what I already do for marathons but have now come to realize, I need to do it in everything in life. The more focused you are on the moment, the richer the experience and better the result. If you are focused on result, you'll miss the details and vital lessons of the moment. Those are my thoughts for the day heehee
